==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stanchion
<hw>Stan"chion</hw> <pr>(st⟦acr⟧n"sh⟦ucr⟧n ; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[OF. <ets>estanson</ets>, <ets>estan⟦cced⟧on</ets>, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧tan⟦cced⟧on</ets>, from OF. <ets>estance</ets> a stay, a
prop, from L. <ets>stans</ets>, <ets>stantis</ets>, standing, p. pr. of
<ets>stare</ets> to stand. See <er>Stand</er>, and cf.
<er>Stanza</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>stanchel</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A prop
or support; a piece of timber in the form of a stake or post, used for a
support or stay.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>Any upright post or beam used as
a support, as for the deck, the quarter rails, awnings, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A vertical bar for confining cattle in a
stall.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stanchless</ent>⟦br⟧
